  "articleSummary": "The article argues that using a static dropdown for ticket Priority (e.g., P1‑P4) is a “priority trap” that quickly devolves into an ever‑inflating hierarchy (P0, P00, etc.) that no longer reflects real‑world urgency or value. It illustrates the problem with a startup‑style Jira story, then frames the issue as a metaphor for “z‑index wars” and other unbounded numeric fields, warning that unchecked growth can even exceed data‑type limits. The author recommends replacing the hard‑coded list with more flexible approaches—numeric scales, composite scores, or dynamic methods like MoSCoW or the Kano model—and urges regular backlog pruning and clear separation of severity (urgency) from priority. The tone is a mix of informal rant and practical analysis aimed at engineers, product managers, and anyone responsible for backlog grooming in growing organizations.",
